11. Cum Hanno perorasset, nemini omnium certare ora-

tain possession of Tarentum, which was an infringement of the treaty3 for it had been stipulated that they should refrain from making any conquests in Italy. The circumstance occurred at the conclu- sion of the war between the Romans and King Pyrrhus. After the departure of the king the Romans besieged Tarentum, whereupon a Carthaginian ficet appeared near the harbour‚ and the commander offered assistance to the Tarentines. This compelled the Romans to grant the townsmen more advantageous conditions of surrender than they otherwise would have done. And this dispute appears, at least according to Hanno's representations. to have been the occasion of further hostilities between the two nations.
